journal_entry: rainy build Coal bin wrote letter to Hale & Emery Ellworth Me.
Went on Gridstone point after Oxen hauled home one load coal from John Lark from Rockland price of coal 6.50 per ton
hauled home 3 loads coal cut down a piece of oats Acknowledge deed for N. Hammond
The wind North West commenced to burn coal took dunnage out of vessel
The wind Southerly very moderate got coal out of vessel and brought scow around to the shore to get wood in
The wind North West heavy blow and cold worked on board vessel in forenoon. put coal fixtursin stove and commenced burning coal in afternoon.

The wind very moderate Westerly got two Bbls coal home and went on the shore and Married Mr Henry Bunker and Miss Hattie Bunker both of Gouldsboro came back and went to Hall meeting and was chosen secretary
The wind westerly and pleasant set up rigging and mending sails towed into the wharf in Charlestown to discharge coal wrote letter home recd one from home
The wind Easterly Commenced discharging coal
The wind Easterly went on board the Schr Henrietta and went to Rockland to buy coal and provisions for winter. arrived at five oclock P.M. and went into Atlantic wharf.
The wind Easterly went on board the Schr Henrietta and went to Rockland to buy coal and provisions for winter. arrived at five oclock P.M. and went into Atlantic wharf.
The wind North West hauled the Schr Henrietta into the wharf and took out coal and hauled it home.
Wind very moderate Southerly Hauled the Sea Queen into the Wharf and took one ton of coal out. that was left in by the Stevedores when we discharged in Boston.

Wind SouthWest had vessels bottom painted and vessel put in the water. Being discharged about getting a suitable Charter to go upshore I took acoal order to go tp Port Johnson and load with coal for Portsmouth NH at $1.35 per ton. Went Port Johnson at night.

Got underway. At 5.30vin the morning at Port Johnson loaded with coal. On board the Schr. Chromo. My first trip in her. Wind West Went through Hell gate with a pilot at noon. at 8 o.clock in evening passed between Stratford and middle ground. At midnight the end of this year 1882 Abrest of Falkners Island. in Long Island Soud bound to Portsmouth. N.H. The sky overcast and very dark.

Got underway. At 5.30vin the morning at Port Johnson loaded with coal. On board the Schr. Chromo. My first trip in her. Wind West Went through Hell gate with a pilot at noon. at 8 o.clock in evening passed between Stratford and middle ground. At midnight the end of this year 1882 Abrest of Falkners Island. in Long Island Soud bound to Portsmouth. N.H. The sky overcast and very dark.

Wind moderate Easterly with snow most all day. Went on board Chromo, and came in to the Harbor with vessel and help break the the ice in the Harbor so the Nevada and A. Hooper could move hauled Chromo into the wharf to take out some coal

Wind NorthWest work in shop on various kinds of work. In the afternoon Henry Sargents house and barn was burned. to gather with 3 1/2 coals Pray & a years moved prepared for the stove, furniture saved

Wind Westerly also Thanksgiving Towed Chromo out of New Town Creek. made sail and went as far as Robbins Reef. Took tug boat and towed to Elizabeth port arriving at one P.M. at 3.45 commenced loading Coal for Bar Harbor to freight $1.35 per ton and discharged. At 5.15 oclock was loaded with 199 tons. Got ship stores in evening

Wind from South West to West. towed out the coal dock at Elizabeth port in morning. made sail and anchored at the Red Hook at 10 a.m. Went to the City of N.Y. and settled the freight on the load of lumber I brouht here. Sent J.P. Gordon a check bore so for owners of Chromo Shiped a man got on board at 4 P.M. and am all ready to sail for Bar Harbor

Wind North. Commenced work again in the noon to discharge coal and at 3 PM was all discharged soon after dark vessel was afloat sum kedy hauled of made sail and went to Winter Harbor arrived at 9 P.M. wind very moderate when anchored

Wind East North East and snowy all day. hauled up to the Dhouse ton of coal that came out the "Chromo" that I have been in for the past year. Took Sch Egret from the Steam boat wharf and took her to our own wharf to look after the remainder of the winter Price agreceived upon $5.00. In the evening went to the Steam boat wharf meeting at Winter Harbor Sleighing good.

Wind Southerly commenced discharging cargo of stone. Went to town in the forenoon and took a coal order (without any help of a broker). to go Portsmouth N.H. with a load of coal freight $1.10 to be loaded at Port Johnston. In the afternoon went to Coney Island with my wife Took the Steamer on the North River and went to Bay Ridge then took the Cars to Coney Island Came back at night to the Chromo. The fare for Gentleman 40 cents and return. And for ladies 35 cts. Received letter today that Stella Our girl at home is sick but on the mending hand

Wind Northerly commenced loading In the forenoon but did not get loaded untill three oclock PM got bill of Laden and towed from the coal dock at Port Johnson to Rickers Island and anchored there at 7.30 PM with a very light air N.N.E bound to Boston

Wind moderate and baffling. at 10.30 am when the wind got fixed SouthWest. got underway at Booth bay but when the sun set we were of Musquito Island the wind came of Northerly and looked very bad and at 7 oclock PM passed into the Mussle Ridges and anchored in Lobster coal
Wind North West and cold. Finished hauling my coal home from the Steam boat wharf
Wind South Made a litter for boat finished haying hauled in 16 cocks went to Temperance lecture in evening Mr Hansenn & Mrs Fremeh
Took Hayrick apart put it away done some chored up for fall
The wind W.N.W. blowed heavy. commenced farming plowing
The wind W.N.W. farming plowing Geo. Pendleton taken for stealing acknowledge the deed breaking into C. Stevens store
The wind southerly foggy farming planting corn squashes beans pumpkins potatoes peas etc.
The wind Southly foggy work for Edmond Grover with team farming
The wind N.W.and.S.W finished farming in the oat field painted closer etc. went to Lodge of Good Templars
The wind N.N.W. commenced haying
The wind N.W. commenced haying again put up 28 stacks
The wind N.W all day went to Bar Harbor after ship stores for the Schr Signal hauled in the last load of hay, recd letters from G. N. Loomis G. L. Hodgkins
The wind N.W all day went to Bar Harbor after ship stores for the Schr Signal hauled in the last load of hay, recd letters from G. N. Loomis G. L. Hodgkins
The wind out Southerly worked apart of fore noon farming for the first time in 1874
The wind North East work farming
The wind Northerly in forenoon S.W. afternoon got provisions on board in fore noon work farming in afternoon
The wind South West commenced haying
The wind North West and pleasant haying hauled in 15 stacks
The wind Westerly haying hauled in 12 stacks of hay
The wind Southerly haying hauled in 12 stacks of hay
The wind Northerly and Easterly over cast poor hay day mowed all forenoon raked in afternoon finished mowing
The wind Southerly hayed in 18 stacks of hay
The wind Southerly clear and warm opened hay and hauled in one load of 20 stacks
The wind NorthWest and pleasant opened hay turned it hauled in 36 stacks of hay
The wind Easterly and pleasant. getting ready to do some farming
The wind N.N.W. Commenced haying mowing in forenoon
The wind Southerly poor hay day. work in shop
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind N. West. and pleasant went on Egg Rock to see the walls of the new Light house. polled in 6 stacks of hay in the after noon.
The wind N. West. and pleasant went on Egg Rock to see the walls of the new Light house. polled in 6 stacks of hay in the after noon.
The wind N. West. and pleasant went on Egg Rock to see the walls of the new Light house. polled in 6 stacks of hay in the after noon.
The wind Southerly mowed in forenoon hauled in 19 stacks of hay in afternoon
The wind Southerly hauled in 10 stacks of hay mowed in fore noon raked up in afternoon
The wind N. W. very fine day mowed in forenoon hauled in 15 stacks of hay in afternoon
The wind North West. hauled in 30 stacks of hay
The wind Easterly hauled in 25 stacks of hay. heavy rain in afternoon.
The wind Northerly in morning and Southerly in afternoon hauled in 20 stacks of hay and finished haying
The wind Northerly fine breeze. work for J. F. Kingsley haying all day wrote letter to C Stevens Esqr and Hancock Co pub Co.
The wind Southerly haying for J.F. Kingsley
The wind South work haying J.F. Kingsley
The wind N.W. in forenoon and Southerly in afternoon. Work all day haying J.F. Kingsley
The wind Southerly Helped J. F. Kingsley apart of the day getting hay
The wind Southerly Thermometer 54 Commenced farming in morning and finished at night with the help of Charles Harrington at night very heavy rain
The wind Southerly Thermometer 62 degrees helped J.F. Kingsley in the afternoon get his hay. Bought one half ton of hay and put it in T.R. Hammonds barn
The wind Northerly Thermometer 68° in the forenoon and overcast in the afternoon clear weather Thermometer 72° help J Kingsley all day haying.
The wind North West. Thermometer 74 degrees Work for J.F. Kingsley haying. hauled in five loads
The wind Southerly Thermometer 72 degrees work for J.F. Kingsley hauled in two loads of hay.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 58 moderate rain in the afternoon. Hauled one load of hay in barn in forenoon for J.F.K
The wind North West Thermometer 72 degrees Help J.F. Kingsley haul in 4 loads of hay. had party from Bar Harbor to stay over night
The wind North West Thermometer 72 degrees Help J.F. Kingsley haul in 4 loads of hay. had party from Bar Harbor to stay over night
The wind Southerly helped J.F. Kingsley on his hay finished mowing Company left for Bar Harbor Recd letter from Boston Post Went to W Gouldsboro at night and got some ice.
The wind Southerly helped J.F. Kingsley on his hay finished mowing Company left for Bar Harbor Recd letter from Boston Post Went to W Gouldsboro at night and got some ice.
The wind Southerly helped J.F. Kingsley on his hay finished mowing Company left for Bar Harbor Recd letter from Boston Post Went to W Gouldsboro at night and got some ice.
The wind moderate Southerly and overcast. Thermometer 58 degrees Hauled in load of hay and left it on the rack
Very moderate all day with an air of wind all around the compass The Thermometer 73 above bought one ton of hay of J.T. Kingsley and hauled it home. Helped Colen Pendleton on his dora to make tight

The wind South South East. Thermometer 50 degrees Commenced farming plowed all the forenoon with the help of Henry Sargents cattle. in the afternoon showery and foggy. Farming on the land formerly of the Stephen Rand Estate.

The wind northerly in forenoon and pleasant Thermometer 60° and in the afternoon the wind South West Thermometer 45 work in the afternoon farming with the help of Simon Sargent and Joseph Bickford Saw the Genil Agt of Ln Lewiston
The wind North West. Thermometer 62 degrees work all day farming planting beans Corn Squashes &c
The wind North. Thermometer 51 degrees sewed Cumbers seed and work on the place all day farming
The wind Westerly Thermometer 53 degrees work all day farming for my self.

The wind Came of in the forenoon North West and pleasant. Thermometer 57 degrees wrote letters to Boston Post Daily Traveller and Chas Mckey all of Boston. Went to Prospect and got 450 lbs hay for myself settled with Jennie Tracy

The wind Came of in the forenoon North West and pleasant. Thermometer 57 degrees wrote letters to Boston Post Daily Traveller and Chas Mckey all of Boston. Went to Prospect and got 450 lbs hay for myself settled with Jennie Tracy

The wind Southerly and overcast Thermometer 50 Went to South Gouldsboro Steam boat wharf to cary Miss Greenleaf to take the Str Mt Deserrt. Mowed some hay in the afternoon and poled some in the barn at night.

The wind Southerly and overcast Thermometer 50 Went to South Gouldsboro Steam boat wharf to cary Miss Greenleaf to take the Str Mt Deserrt. Mowed some hay in the afternoon and poled some in the barn at night.

The wind Southerly and overcast Thermometer 50 Went to South Gouldsboro Steam boat wharf to cary Miss Greenleaf to take the Str Mt Deserrt. Mowed some hay in the afternoon and poled some in the barn at night.
The wind North pleasant Thermometer 59 degrees took care of hay that was mowed before the storm. The wind South West at 4.P.M.
The wind North West in the forenoon & South West in the afternoon Thermometer 62° work all day haying wrote letters to Mrs Bessie E Crant and M. Gallart &Co. received letter from Miss Guenlief
The wind Easterly Thermometer 60 and overcast mowed in the forenoon but did not open or spread my for hay day
The wind North West Thermometer 67 degrees Finished the mast step in the Hayward yatch. Went to South Gouldsboro wharf with my boarders trunks
The wind Southerly Thermometer 55° Took up my troll to do other work with the intention of heeping it uo untill after I do some farming. Turned Acorn and ball to go on Spire of Chapel.
Wind Southerly & foggy Commenced farming plowed all day with the help of Henry Sargent. Acknowledged deed for A.J.Baker Thermometer 65
Wind Southerly and pleasant Thermometer. 65 degrees Work about home farming Mr Asher Palmer Ordainedin the evening.
Wind West North West Thermometer 68 degrees Work all day farming. plowing and hauling dressing. Received a Check from the Post Office for $12.38 for Carrying mail. Route 365
Wind East fresh breeze and clear Thermometer 65 work all day farming covering potatoes and hauling dresing
Wind South Easterly and thick with fog Thermometer 68 work about house. wrote letter to C. Y. Bunker Commenced haying for my self.
The wind Southerly and thick with gof untill 10 am when the wind came from the westward and the sun came out work all day haying at 4 P.M. wind Southerly again and thick
The wind North West in forenoon & South West in afternoon. Work all day haying Thermometer at Noon 84 degrees ar night cooler
The wind North West in the forenoon & South West in afternoon work all day haying hauled in 12 stacks of hay Thermometer 86 degrees at noon
The wind North West untill the middle of the afternoon. then South West Thermometer 78 degrees Work all day haying hauled in 77 stacks of hay

Wind North West in forenoon South West in afternoon work all day haying hauled in 51 stacks of hay. Thermometer at noon was 78 degrees high received letter from C. J. Abbot. Atty at Law. Casting called for advertising in Boston Traveller.
Wind Southerly all day Thermometer at noon 81° hauled in one load of hay about 24 stacks.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 32 degrees At home weighing hay for J. H. Kingsley & JennieTracy.
The wind South East Thermometer 33 degrees Work in the forenoon for H E Tracy. In the afternoon weighed hay for Jennie Tracy
The wind Easterly Thermometer 38 dehrees Weighed hay for Jennie Tracy and worked on my dora
Wind North West Thermometer 42 above made centre box for my dora sold and weighed hay for Chas Smith
The wind South East Thermometer 67 degrees Commenced farming done all ploving Recd execution against J. L. Andrews for me to collect as Constable from the Office of Geo M Warren G. Stevens Plaintiff
The wind South West work all day farming with J.F.Kingsleys horse and the help of Geo. Gerrish Finished hauling out dressing and planted corn beans & c. Thermometer 50
The wind E. S. East and pleasant Thermometer 62 degrees bought of James A Stevens 2 Hds salt and got it a shore finished sewing garden and all farming for the spring Recd letter from J.H.West

Wind Northerly in forenoon Clement Bunker Came to do my farming. In morning I held plow untill 9 oclock in forenoon and left linn and went on board the Sea Queen to go out for Franklin Island. At one PM took the wind out when abrest of onter end of Iron Bound. Anchored at Sullivan at 3 Went ashore got new Coasting Licence. At 5 got underway and went over Falls and up to Franklin At Sunset went ashore and agreceived to load for J.P. Gordon with Granite paving blocks for New York at $26 per 1.000

Wind Northerly in forenoon Clement Bunker Came to do my farming. In morning I held plow untill 9 oclock in forenoon and left linn and went on board the Sea Queen to go out for Franklin Island. At one PM took the wind out when abrest of onter end of Iron Bound. Anchored at Sullivan at 3 Went ashore got new Coasting Licence. At 5 got underway and went over Falls and up to Franklin At Sunset went ashore and agreceived to load for J.P. Gordon with Granite paving blocks for New York at $26 per 1.000

Wind Northerly in forenoon Clement Bunker Came to do my farming. In morning I held plow untill 9 oclock in forenoon and left linn and went on board the Sea Queen to go out for Franklin Island. At one PM took the wind out when abrest of onter end of Iron Bound. Anchored at Sullivan at 3 Went ashore got new Coasting Licence. At 5 got underway and went over Falls and up to Franklin At Sunset went ashore and agreceived to load for J.P. Gordon with Granite paving blocks for New York at $26 per 1.000

Wind Southerly and in forenoon thick with fog. Was about home all day. agreceived with Chas Straw to get the hay. let the Workshop to Mr. Staples for $1. per mouth for a tin shop paid the taxes fo the year. Settled accts with Capt N. Hammond

Wind Easterly. At 10 AM Nichols Bunker came from West Gouldsboro and bought Mr Kingsleys horse In the forenoon hauled a load of hay out to the sheep. and in the afternoon work on GW. Tracys boom. snowy
Wind NorthEast and in the afternoon snow hauled a load of hay to the back field, and cleared up the shop chamber

Wind South West and warm. hauled hay from my barn to Mrs Kingsleys sheep house In the afternoon went to District meeting to see about dividing the School house into two rooms. but the District did not agree and the School house is not to be divided by a partittan running through as was in the warrant. and the meeting adjourned
Wind SouthWest Sold one halfton hay to J J Roberts In the evening went to the Masonic meeting at the Hall
The wind N.W. plowing in the forenoon and in the afternoon getting ready to go a fishing
The wind N.E.and.S.W went a fishing got 20 Codfish in the Mermaid
The wind N. East went fishing raining read letters from Geo. A. Dyer. Arno Wiswell. Charles C. Burrill all of Ellsworth also one from Perley and Russell of Portland.
The wind East and clear went out fishing got 9 went to lodge of Good Templars in evening rainy at 10 PM.
The wind Southerly and Easterly started out fishing moderate and came back finished roping jib top sail. Hauled home stove and half doz chairs
The wind North West went a fishing A. squall of rain and hail at night went to Lodge of Good Templars
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind N.N.W went lobstering in morning. and opened hay in the afternoon. went down on Turtle Island and got fish of Alvin Foss put up the hay at night. Recd letter from James Chilcott
The wind Southerly and foggy. work in garden washed out fish and work in shop finished the Crib.
THe wind Westerly in the forenoon and South West in the afternoon went on turtle Island and got some fish of Alvin Foss
THe wind Westerly in the forenoon and South West in the afternoon went on turtle Island and got some fish of Alvin Foss
THe wind Westerly in the forenoon and South West in the afternoon went on turtle Island and got some fish of Alvin Foss
The wind W.N.W. Port falde bottom. on fora for Alvin Foss and washed out some fish
The wind Northerly Clear Thermometer 52 degrees In the afternoon went down to Schoodic Island and built a tank to pall fish in for Jabez Myriek stoped on the Island all night
The wind moderate Easterly and fine weather Thermometer 50 Commenced repairing Warren Smith Skiff in the fish house In the Evening Steam boat wharf meeting.
The wind North North west. Work all day on boat for Warren Smith in the fish house. Thermometer 35 degrees above zero.
The wind North East Thermometer 35 degrees Administered the oath to the P.M. quarterly returns took my boat out of the fishouse that I have been repairing.
Wind North East. work 3/4 day shingling for Capt N.A.Bickford & finished work. and at night baited troll ready to go a fishing Thermometer 44 degrees
Calm in morning went out fishing and set troll in Egg Rock Channel got one 1 a half tubs of fish back in the afternoon wind South West fresh breeze Thermometer 57 degrees
Wind Easterly and heavy rain in morning Cleared up in the afternoon made a floaling stage to dress fish on Thermometer 70°
Wind South West Thermometer. 60° Work about the fish house all day putting it in order to take care of fish.
The wind Easterly in forenoon went out to my troll got two tubs of fish and came back about 4 oclock. wind Southerly and the Thermometer 37 degrees.
The wind South East Thermometer 50 degrees went out to my troll fishing wrote letter to A. P. Wiswell
Wind Westerly Thermometer 65 Registered letter to A.P.Wiswell with $15. enclosed the ballance due on my Insolvency Staid in from fishing to put Cork rope and sinker line on net.

The wind Southerly and foggy all day Thermometer 50 degrees. took six Hhds salts out of the Black Warrior to use fishing Worked 1/2 day for Barney Foss on his boat to make her tight. received letter from Clarance Hale. Portland.
Wind Northerly in morning went out fishing and set troll wind Southerly in the afternoon took up troll and went home. Thermometer 70°
Wind Easterly and Thermometer 59 degrees Started out fishing no bait came back and worked on place
Wind East Thermometer 56 drizzling rain. Went out fishing Fannie Pendleton burried in afternoon
Wind Southerly all day Thermometer 71 degrees Went out fishing
Wind Southerly all day Thermometer 62 degrees. Went to my net but not bait enough to go afishing baited my troll at night
The wind North West. Thermometer 60 degrees wind blew fresh went out fishing in dora. Heavy rain Showers at night wind form the North.
Wind North West very fresh breeze to much wind to go a fishing Thermometer 59 work a bout the fish house all day.
The wind Southerly and the Thermometer 65 degrees Went out fishing
The wind baffling from North East to South East moderate and overcast Went out fishing from home in dora.
Very early in the morning wind Easterly and very heavy thunder and rain. at 8 Am. moderate and cleared up went out fishing Thermometer 69.
The wind South West. Thermometer 67 degrees Went out fishing. Wrote letter to G. H. Smith
The wind South South West Thermometer 79 degrees Went out fishing. foggy in forenoon cleared up in afternoon
Calm in the morning went out fishing from home in dora. At noon heavy shower. Afternoon Southerly wind and foggy. Ther Thermometer at noon 81 degrees.
Calm in the forenoon South West wind in afternoon. Thermometer 72 degrees at noon Went out fishing
Southerly wind in morning Went out fishing at 10 Am heavy thunder with rain squalls at night foggy Thermometer 67 degrees,
Calm and rainy all day Thermometer 60° Went out fishing
The wind Southerly and Thermometer. 72 degrees Worked 3/4 of a day for Alexander Bickford on the Schr Henry Clay fishing foremast
The wind Southerly and the Sea rough Went out fishing Thermometer 85 degrees
Wind Southerly and moderate went out fishing Thermometer 69° plenty of Mackerel to be caught in nets
The wind Easterly and moderate Thermometer 70° Went out fishing from home in dora and back in the afternoon. That being my business this summer when there is bait to fish with
The wind Southerly Thick with fog Thermometer 70 degrees went out fishing
The wind South and thick with fog. Went out fishing Thermometer 61 degrees
The wind Southerly and overcast partially foggy went out fishing Thermometer 71 degrees,
The wind Northerly in forenoon went out fishing Wind Southerly in afternoon Thermometer 72 Wrote letter to Geo M Waren Castine.

The wind very moderate all day and fine weather went out fishing from home in dora. Thermometer in the afternoon when I came in from fishing 80 degrees. received letter from Helen Stevens at Leadsvelle
Thick with fog in morning at 10 Am cleared up Went out fishing very fresh breeze Southerly Thermometer 74 degrees
Wind Southerly and moderate all day. Went out fishing Thermometer 79 degrees Catching mackerel mornand night for troll bait
Wind Northerly in morning Went out fishing Wind Southerly in afternoon Thermometer 78 degrees received Check from the Post Office Department for &12.38 for Mail service on Route 365
Calm in the morning went out fishing from home in dora. Wind South West in afternoon came home Thermometer 79 degrees
Moderate Southerly all day. Went out fishing from home in dora. back in afternoon Thermometer 75 degrees
Very fresh Southerly all day and rough Went out fishing from home in dora Thermometer 62 degrees
The wind South Easterly and moderate. Went to my troll fishing from home. and using salt bait. got about 3/4 of a tub of fish Thermometer 68°
Calm and thick with fog. Went out fishing heavy rain at noon Thermometer 57 degrees.
Wind South West Went out fishing to the South of Egg rock using mackerel for bait from home in dora Thermometer. 71 degrees
Wind Southerly Went out fishing Thermometer 79 degrees.
Wind North all day very fresh breeze. blew so hard I could not go fishing staid home and Coopered Hhds &c Thermometer 71 degrees
Wind North West in forenoon Went ou fishing Wind South West in afternoon Wrote deed for P L Tracy in evening. Thermometer 60 degrees
Wind Southerly and moderate went out fishing from home in dora. Thermometer 70 degrees.
Wind North North West Went out a fishing from home living on the Wm Handy place purchased by my wife May 28th Thermometer 61 degrees
Wind South West Went out fishing using herring for bait. fish not very plenty, a good school of haddock in the spring but hake are very scarce.
Wind South West Staid in from fishing to do other work went to Prospect Harbor to Cary My wife to make an Endorsment . on note
The wind Southerly and a very fresh breeze did not go a fishing Thermometer 70 degrees

Wind Southerly and Thermometer 70 degrees Wrote letter to Wm Handy Owner of Schr Old Chad Geo. M. Warren and to the Post Office Department last named letter for David Weare. Went out fishing afternoon
The wind South. rough weather for fishing Thermometer 49 degrees
The wind North West in forenoon and Calm in afternoon Went outfishing Thermometer 60 degrees.
Wind North West and a very fresh breeze to much wind to go fishing Thermometer 55 degrees
Wind North West and very fresh breeze Went out fishing in dora from home making the fishing business my general employment. Thermometer 45 degrees.
Wind North West in the morning got 2 bushels of herring for bait in my net. Went out fishing Wind South South West in afternoon. and the Thermometer 31° in morning very heavy frost
Wind Southerly and thermometer 75 degrees did not go a fishing for the want of bait washed out fish for my self received letter from R H Bickford wrote one to Clarance Hane & Geo Warren.
Wind Southerly and clear Thermometer 74 got no bait in nets and. did not go a fishing Work most all day on wagon wheel for my self. A man hired to dig potatoes.
Wind Southerly and heavy frost Thermometer 34 in morning Went out fishing got a little. more than one tub of fish. Heavy frost at night.
The wind South South West blowing heavy and big sea running could not get out fishing and worked about home. Thermometer 47 degrees at sunset.
Wind Northerly in morning went out fishing and swept for the lost troll got it in the afternoon Winf South west. Thermometer 61 degrees,
Wind South west. fresh breeze Went out a fishing Thermometer at sunset 49 degrees
Wind South West thick. and blowy. Went out fishing Thermometer 59 degrees
Wind North West and fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 33 degrees and at noon 60 degrees work about home on fish
Wind North in the morning Went out fishing with Barney Foss. got one tub of large hake to my part wind southerly in afternoon Thermometer 54 degrees received letter from W. F. Vase.
Wind Westerly. and a very fresh breeze with Thermometer 37 degrees at noon Washed out some fish for myself.
Wind Westerly and fresh breeze with the Thermometer 38 degrees worked on my troll in forenoon and in the afternoon. Made window frame for the fishouse that Geo Gerrish fixing to move in
Wind Northerly in morning Thermometer 31° heavy frost. Went out fishing Wind Southerly in afternoon Thermometer 50 degrees
Wind South fresh breeze and cloudy Went out fishing. Thermometer at dark when I got home 49 degrees. received letter from Henry Handy
Wind North in morning Thermometer 47 degrees In afternoon wind S. East finished digging my potatoes Geo Gerrish moved in the fish house
The wind North North West Thermometer in morning 31° Started out fishing went as far as Spectacle Island got no bait and came home.
The wind North West and a very fresh breeze in afternoon wind moderate went out fishing on Schr head ground. back in the evening Thermometer 50
The wind Easterly and overcast Went on Martins ground fishing alone. Wind increased to a moderate gale. got home in afternoon Thermometer 48°
Wind Westerly and quite moderate in the afternoon wind came of with rain squalls. Thermometer 42° Salted fish caught yesterday. and getting ready for other work.
Wind North West very fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 28 degrees. Work apart of the forenoon for Thomas Bickford in afternoon took fish out of bults ready to ship
Wind North West very fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 28 degrees. Work apart of the forenoon for Thomas Bickford in afternoon took fish out of bults ready to ship
Wind North West very fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 28 degrees. Work apart of the forenoon for Thomas Bickford in afternoon took fish out of bults ready to ship
The wind Easterly moderate Thermometer 26 degrees at sunrise. Wind increased to a gale with rain in the afternoon put my fish on board of the Ida C Spofford to ship by Capt James A. Stevens
The wind North East light snow in the morning then turned to drizzling rain Roped dora sail and geting ready to go fishing
The wind North west Thermometer 39 degrees bailed trall ready to go fishing tomorrow Stephan Torrey burried in afternoon a prayer at the house by A.T. Palmer

The wind Northerly in morning went out fishing for the first time for the season got 9 wind Southerly at noon came home. Thermometer 35 degrees Jennie Hammond burried in afternoon Seruises at the house by A T Palmer

Calm in morning went out fishing picked the troll twice got 14 fish at noon the wind breezed up South west and came home. Wrote Notice for District meeting in district No. 12 which is at the Lower Harbor Thermometer 37.
Wind South East Thermometer 33 moved Geo. Gerrish from the fish house to the one recently bought by Mark Joy. In afternoon made made sink for room occupied by Joseph & Annie Smallidge

Calm and drizzling rain all day Thermometer 62° Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail
The wind S.S.E. Thermometer 58 degrees and rainy all day. Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail then to the Town House to the State Election back to W. Gouldsboro took the mail and came home.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 52° Went to West Gouldsbo with the Mail. Wrote letter to Mr Helen Stevens
The wind Easterly and overcast. Thermometer 49 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail.
Calm in morning very heavy frost Thermometer 26 Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail
The wind Southerly Thermometer 45° Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. received letter from Helen Stevens.
The wind Easterly and drizzling rain Thermometer 52 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail.
The wind North West And Thermometer 36 Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail. heavy Snow Squalls in forenoon.
The wind South West Thermometer 60° Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail Repaired the Schr AGBrooks wheel. received letter from Boston Traveler Office.
The wind West N. West. and a very fresh breeze Thermometer 33 degrees went to West Gouldsboro with the mail.
The wind Westerly Thermometer 44 degrees Went to South Gouldsboro to get Leonard Bunker to Cary the mail for me tomorrow.

The wind Easterly Thermometer 35 degrees Snow and rain to gather Went to West gouldsboro with the mail, good Sleighign at West Gouldsboro Hauled wood from the shore to the house at night Let David Weare have my horse to go on Mail Router.

The wind North West fresh breeze and the Thermometer 28 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail on Route 191 Via Prospect. received check from Mr Wm. B. Viall for $12.38 for carrying mail one gr on Route 365. West Gouldsboro

The wind Southerly Thermometer 45 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail. Capt L.B. Tracy burried at Winter Harbor in the afternoon. Who died on board his vessel at Kittery Point. at night rainy.

The wind Southerly Thermometer 45 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail. Capt L.B. Tracy burried at Winter Harbor in the afternoon. Who died on board his vessel at Kittery Point. at night rainy.
The wind Westerly and Thermometer 41 degrees not any snow. or ice took some dishes out the Hotel Went to So. Gouldsboro and got. Leonard Bunker to carry the Mail.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 40 above moderate rain and snow all day. Went to West Gouldsboro. with the mail.

The wind from South West to W. Thermometer 40 degrees above 0 Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. received letter from the Auditor of the Treasury for the Post Office Department stahing check sent me No 14872 lost and payment stoped at Po in Portland
The wind North West Thermometer 28 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. Wrote to Town Clerk to get Charles E. Kingsley and Hannah C Grover Published both of Gouldsboro
The wind Easterly and pleasant. Thermometer 47 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail. Wrote to Port Master at Portland to know if lost check 14872 had been cashed.
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 32 above received letter from the Post Master Portland certifying the mail Route 365 No 14872 had not been paid.
The wind South East Thermometer at zero in morning. Went to South Gouldsboro. and paid Charles L Bunker for Carrying the mail on Route 365. up to Jan 1 1880.
The wind North West Thermometer at zero in the morning. Made a chart of the mail Routes in Gouldsboro to help establish a Post Office in Birch Harbor Work on Warren Smith boat.
The wind North blowing & snowing fearfully The roads blocked with snow so the mail could not go out. the only time for the Winter. Painted my skiff. Thermometer 20° above zero.

The wind North West and in the morning Thermometer 25° Went to West Gouldsboro Oath to the P.M.So.Gouldsboro Hired Wm Bunker to Cary the Mail for a Quarter at $10 home at night received letter from Geo Hopkins Millbridge.
Wind West North West Thermometer 68 degrees Work all day farming. plowing and hauling dressing. Received a Check from the Post Office for $12.38 for Carrying mail. Route 365
Wind Northerly in morning Went out fishing Wind Southerly in afternoon Thermometer 78 degrees received Check from the Post Office Department for &12.38 for Mail service on Route 365

The wind North West and the Thermometer 22 degrees. Went to West Gouldsboro and West-Bay. and Prospect and sold my horse to W. F. Vose. to be delivered monday. received Post Office checks for carying mail Route 365
The wind West North West Thermometer 45 degrees mailed nailed centre board box in dora and caulked it made thorts and painted the inside of dora

The wind North west and pleasant with Thermometer 65 degrees at noon Finished labor on one dora for Mr Petlee of Brooklin and commenced on an other one for his son Filled application for Baker & Smith to cary on business in manufature tobacco. Acknowledged Bill of Sale for A. J. Gerrish Wrote lease from Isaac P Joy to Amasink Southard recd check from the P.O. Department to Cary mail on route 365
The wind North East fresh breeze and heavy rain all day. work apart of the day on wheel barrow. and examined the papers of Wm. Bunkers for carrying the mail
Wind North West. Fresh breeze. Work all the forenoon shoveling snow from the highway In the afternoon roads blocking again wich snow kept it clear enought so the mail could get along
Wind NorthEast Fresh breeze and a heavy snow storm all day and cold. About home doing nothing in particular Mail did not arrive on account of the big storm
Work about home received letter from N. H. Higgins Ins agt.
Came home from camp read a letter from Joseph Bunker & Emery
work in shop received a letter from CC Burrill Ellsworth one from George N Loomis
Jobbing read letter from G. N. Harden M D.
Read letter from CC Burrill went to West Gouldsboro in the Ins. Busi took tea with Edward Kingsley Lodging with Samuel Wood
Read letter from CC Burrill went to West Gouldsboro in the Ins. Busi took tea with Edward Kingsley Lodging with Samuel Wood
received letter from Geo W Tracy. Evening went to Lodge of Good Templars
Breakfast wtih Hannah G dinner with Stephen Kingsly received letter from Hale Emery one from CC burrill came home
Breakfast wtih Hannah G dinner with Stephen Kingsly received letter from Hale Emery one from CC burrill came home
painted boat took dinner at J Smallidges received letter from CC Burrill went to Lodge
went to lobster factory after caned strawberrys received letter from G. W. Tracy went to Lodge of G. Templars
Stormy work in shop received letter from CC Burrill also oil painting of Niagara Falls by moon light went to Lodge of G. Templar lodgign at Thos. Smallidge
Cutting at the door in forenoon received letter from A. Martin Millbridge
Getting out window Jams received letter from C. C. Burrill. dinner at usual place while to work on house
Pretty low with fever received letters of administation of the estate of B Rand
received letter from Chas. C. Burrill
Went to Turtle Island gunning received letters from Hale & Emery Jordan & Blake Perley & Russel G. W. Tracy Went to Lodge
Went to Turtle Island gunning received letters from Hale & Emery Jordan & Blake Perley & Russel G. W. Tracy Went to Lodge
Hauling home brick shingles and boards from S Guptills wharf went to Lodge. received letter from CC Burrill
Work in shop received letter from Hale & Emery went to Lodge of G.T. received letter from Hale & Emery
Repaired windmill received letter from Geo. N. Loomis Lyfe Ins Agt Portsmouth N. H.
Grinding tools in shop received letter from Geo. A. Dyer

The wind NE with slate storm cleared of with the wind N.W. and warm worked in shop made crank for jig saw put on new belt had one load wood hauled by J. Shaw. received letter from Reg. of deeds one from Hale and Emery
The wind west put plank on boat repairing read letters from Reg. of deeds
The wind S.W. painting boat finished caulking read letter from Henry Geyer of Friendship
The wind N. East went fishing raining read letters from Geo. A. Dyer. Arno Wiswell. Charles C. Burrill all of Ellsworth also one from Perley and Russell of Portland.
The wind North North East. cold in morning Worked all day making flying jibboom for Schr. Black Warrior received letter from Wiswell&Wiswell
Calm all day work in shop making chairs received letter from Nahum Rosebrook. met for Rehearsal at G.W.Tracys.store.
Calm all day and warm work in shop in forenoon received letter from Perley & Russel
The wind Northerly. work about home received letter from E.A Baker Boston
The wind North West received letter from Interpreter of Hospital at leghorn. And a speech from Eugene Hale M.C.Playedat the Exhibition in evening.
The wind North in forenoon and Shoutherly in afternoon received letter from Narraguagus Lodge and one from Gale Smith went clamming in morning and work in shop
The wind North East work at home in shop wrote to Hannah Bulger & Chas Hutchings received letter from George Leavy & Wm Dyer
The wind north West fresh breeze and pleasant went to Bar Harbor in my boat. and back received letter from Mejss S. C. Muney Sleo.
The wind North West fresh breeze left Ellsworth at 9 oclock Am in the Sea Flower and got home at 4 oclock PM with furniture for the Hotel. received letters from Frank Spurling & Mary S Stanley
The wind North East. work about. the house. received a letter from Cept E V. Lynam
The wind North East and snowy. all day wrote letter to Mijsrs Maymard Gough &Co. work all day in house painting furniture Received letter from Curtis Stevens
The wind Southerly. very fresh breeze. Went to West Gouldsboro and took the stage and went to Ellsworth to see about. getting money. on Hotel. received letter from Maynard Gough &Co. afternoon rainy
The wind N.N.West. wrote letter to J. A Milliken Cherryfield. Work hauling stone around the house. received letters from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles. And C C Burril at Ellsworth.
The wind Northerly work about home received letters from Mejrs S. C. Muney &Co. Curtis Stevens and Dr S M Lumun

Calm all the forenoon Thermometer 28° above 0 Repaired the sled in the forenoon and in ther afternoon hauled one load of wood out of the woods and the other load that was left on the way. received letter from C. C. Burrill
The wind moderate Westerly Thermometer 8 above. Changed the propeller from any big boat to the little one Shoveled snow apart of the forenoon received letter from Stephen Southard.
Calm in the morning wrote letter to Stephen Southard Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail afternoon wind westerly Thermometer 22 above received letter from Wm B Viall Mail Contractor Bethel Vt.
Calm in the morning wrote letter to Stephen Southard Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail afternoon wind westerly Thermometer 22 above received letter from Wm B Viall Mail Contractor Bethel Vt.
Calm in the morning wrote letter to Stephen Southard Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail afternoon wind westerly Thermometer 22 above received letter from Wm B Viall Mail Contractor Bethel Vt.
The wind Westerly Thermometer 35 above went to West bay to Town meeting was chosen Constable and sworn in received letter from E Stevens
The wind Westerly Thermometer 35 above went to West bay to Town meeting was chosen Constable and sworn in received letter from E Stevens

The wind North East Thermometer 12 above 0 Went to West Gouldsboro to Cary Rebecca Tracy to take the stage for Hancock. Work one half day for Wm Guptill. Snowing all day received letter from Warren Smith Lamoine.

The wind North East Thermometer 12 above 0 Went to West Gouldsboro to Cary Rebecca Tracy to take the stage for Hancock. Work one half day for Wm Guptill. Snowing all day received letter from Warren Smith Lamoine.

The wind North East Thermometer 12 above 0 Went to West Gouldsboro to Cary Rebecca Tracy to take the stage for Hancock. Work one half day for Wm Guptill. Snowing all day received letter from Warren Smith Lamoine.
The wind North West Thermometer 20 above and pleasant Work all day for Wm Guptill on house received letter from the auditor of the Treasurer for the Post Office Department.

The wind South East. Thermometer 39° above worked out half day for Wm Guptill on house. Went to West Gouldsboro to see about P.O.Business. wrote letters to Wm B Viall and Auditor of the P.O.Department received letters from Linda SMallidge & Wm B Viall

The wind South East. Thermometer 39° above worked out half day for Wm Guptill on house. Went to West Gouldsboro to see about P.O.Business. wrote letters to Wm B Viall and Auditor of the P.O.Department received letters from Linda SMallidge & Wm B Viall

The wind South East. Thermometer 39° above worked out half day for Wm Guptill on house. Went to West Gouldsboro to see about P.O.Business. wrote letters to Wm B Viall and Auditor of the P.O.Department received letters from Linda SMallidge & Wm B Viall
The wind Westerly Thermometer 32 degrees Sent Postal to S.W.Libly received letter from Wm Viall work about home cutting wood at the door the sleighing good
The wind South East moderate Thermometer 22 Turned set lounge legs for Reuban Rand. received letters from Han Elias J Hale of Tux Cruft. and Wm B. Viall of Betherl At night was sick.
The wind Westerly. The thermometer 32° Was sick all day and unable to go out to work had medicine of Dr Moore. received letter from B.T. Atherton the Depty Sherriff of Mt Desert.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 35 above. Went to West Gouldsboro to trade harness with Stephen Kingsley took Jennie Tracy up for a sleigh ride received letters from Sloan &Co and Annie Hammond.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 35 above. Went to West Gouldsboro to trade harness with Stephen Kingsley took Jennie Tracy up for a sleigh ride received letters from Sloan &Co and Annie Hammond.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 35 above. Went to West Gouldsboro to trade harness with Stephen Kingsley took Jennie Tracy up for a sleigh ride received letters from Sloan &Co and Annie Hammond.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 34 above 0 received letter from Mr Francis Whiting of Pittsburg Pa
The wind Easterly Thermometer 30 above wrote letter to Eias Hale and Wm. P Joy Esq. received letters from Mejsis Sloaan &Co. X Wamn Smithal Calais

The wind South East Thermometer 39. above above mail for David Weare to West Gouldsboro Via Porspect Route 191 received letter from Wm P. Joy Esqr at night misty or fine rain Crossed Jones Pond on may with the mail

The wind South East Thermometer 39. above above mail for David Weare to West Gouldsboro Via Porspect Route 191 received letter from Wm P. Joy Esqr at night misty or fine rain Crossed Jones Pond on may with the mail

The wind South East Thermometer 39. above above mail for David Weare to West Gouldsboro Via Porspect Route 191 received letter from Wm P. Joy Esqr at night misty or fine rain Crossed Jones Pond on may with the mail

The wind North West. Work one half day for A.J. Gerrish in the afternoon worked half day for J A Stevens making bow sprit. received letter from Helen Stevens. Sold one set Casters in the evening Thermometer 38 degrees

Thermometer 50 degrees. The wind South West in forenoon and North West in the afternoon. Reg letter to Stevens &Co. for Sewing Machine Caster Work apart of the day for A. J. Gerrish on vessel and the rem for R Pendleton on boat received letter from Agt of Lts Lewiston.
The wind Southerly and in the forenoon rainy Thermometer 44 afternoon Cleared up received letter from Stephen Southard Helped Char Pendleton work on dora.
The wind North East. Thermometer 34 degrees worked 3/4 day for A.M Torry. on Schr Mars Hill at 3.PM commenced to rain stoped work. received letter from Sloan &CO.
The wind South South West Thermometer 55 degrees Came home in the afternoon. received letter from the Auditor of the Post Office Department.

The wind Southerly Thermometer 49 degrees wrote letter to Mr E.A.Baker. Made 2 vite Claim deed for Warren Smith and one for Charles E Smith received letter from Wm B Viall and from Second assistant post Warts Gennd
Calm in the morning Thermometer 45 degrees had the horse showed in morning then went to Hammonds Corner after potatoes and delivered Sewing machine Casters. received letters from Sloan & Co and P.M.

Sond after Dr Johnson for Capt Handy The wind Northerly in the morning and South West at night. Thermometer 49 work apart of the day for Wm Guptill received letters from T.C. Woodman and Wm Viall. Capt Wm Handy Deeds his homestead to Mary E Bunker and she gives a Mortgage back for his maintainance Set

The wind Southerly and rainy in the morning. the remainder of the day foggy. Work apart of the day for Capt Peleg Tracy on his house. received letters from Eldridge I Perry and the Boston Transcript office. Waiting up Capt Handy and set up with him all night

The wind Southerly Thermometer 60 and foggy. Hauled out dressing in the forenoon and in the afternoon rained hard. received letter from Portland Bangor & Machias Steam boat Co received Check from PODepartment
The wind West North West and blowing a gale of wind Thermometer 51° Work in the house making an Attornan received letter from the Boston Post Agt.
The wind North West untill about 4 PM then South West. Thermometer 50 degrees Made Sett Pump boxes for the A.G.Brooks. hired Ice chest of Mr Rice. received letter from Eldridge & Perry & A J Chatto

Moderate North West wind in morning Thermometer 54 Went to Bar Harbor with R. Pendleton to collect debt for Sewing Machine Casters In the afternoon the wind blew very heavy West South West came home at 5 P.M. received letter from James W Davis of Ellsworth.

Moderate North West wind in morning Thermometer 54 Went to Bar Harbor with R. Pendleton to collect debt for Sewing Machine Casters In the afternoon the wind blew very heavy West South West came home at 5 P.M. received letter from James W Davis of Ellsworth.

Moderate North West wind in morning Thermometer 54 Went to Bar Harbor with R. Pendleton to collect debt for Sewing Machine Casters In the afternoon the wind blew very heavy West South West came home at 5 P.M. received letter from James W Davis of Ellsworth.

The wind Easterly Thermometer 52 degrees drizzling rain all day. wrote two bill of sales from Rufus H & Nathan A. Bickford to their wifes received letter from the Salem Post. Mrs Mary Tracy died at 3 oclock in the morning

The wind North West in the morning Finished tank in the forenoon. And in the afternoon work on a shed frame. came home at night Wind South West. received letters from A.W. Gray Sons. and several from advertising agents of Boston. Thermometer 53 Mary Tracy burried in afternoon.

The wind Southerly The thermometer 55 degree Finished cutting the wood at the door filed saur and work about home wrote letters to J.W.Davis at Ellsworth and Boston Courier & Boston Transcript received letters from Home Journal and 5 other advertising agents.

The wind Southerly and clear Thermometer work for R Pendleton on how row boats. received letter from Walter G Maker of Boston. Making inquiry about the price of board at the Eureka House. Went to West Gouldsboro at night heavy rain

The wind Southerly and clear Thermometer work for R Pendleton on how row boats. received letter from Walter G Maker of Boston. Making inquiry about the price of board at the Eureka House. Went to West Gouldsboro at night heavy rain
The wind Southerly Thermometer 69. degrees Work all day for j.F.k. on Homer Guptills barn received letter from Mrs Mary Stanley.
The wind Southerly and Thermometer 71 degrees work apart of the forenoon for Roderick Pendleton on his row boats. received letter from Mrs Chester Stevens.

Calm in the forenoon Went to Steuben after Mrs Chester Stevens for a cook to cook for me at the Eureka House. brought her home at 2.PM Thermometer 72 degrees and the wind Southerly received letter from Mr Walter G Maker of Boston.

Calm in the forenoon Went to Steuben after Mrs Chester Stevens for a cook to cook for me at the Eureka House. brought her home at 2.PM Thermometer 72 degrees and the wind Southerly received letter from Mr Walter G Maker of Boston.

Calm in the forenoon Went to Steuben after Mrs Chester Stevens for a cook to cook for me at the Eureka House. brought her home at 2.PM Thermometer 72 degrees and the wind Southerly received letter from Mr Walter G Maker of Boston.
The wind West North West Thermometer 74 degrees Hoed my beans & Corn received letter from Mrs Henry Chapin and circulars from several advertising agents.
The wind South and rainy and foggy all day at 10 Am no despalh and came home Thermometer 51 degrees received letters from M Gallent &Co. & marden & Rowell.
The wind South and rainy and foggy all day at 10 Am no despalh and came home Thermometer 51 degrees received letters from M Gallent &Co. & marden & Rowell.
The wind North West in the forenoon & South West in the afternoon Thermometer 62° work all day haying wrote letters to Mrs Bessie E Crant and M. Gallart &Co. received letter from Miss Guenlief
The wind Southerly Thermometer 60° and thick with fog Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail. received letter from A.P. Wiswell Esq
The wind Southerly Thermometer 65 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with mail received letter from Chas J Guptill of Steuben Sold my interest in a boat to Mr Ira Foss received $10
The wind Southerly Thermometer 45° Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. received letter from Helen Stevens.

The wind South West Thermometer 67 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro received letter from RH Kittredge &Co and wrote letter to R H Kittredge & Co and to A P Wiswell Esq. oath o G W Tracy as Post master.
The wind South West Thermometer 60° Went to West Gouldsboro with the Mail Repaired the Schr AGBrooks wheel. received letter from Boston Traveler Office.

The wind from South West to W. Thermometer 40 degrees above 0 Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. received letter from the Auditor of the Treasury for the Post Office Department stahing check sent me No 14872 lost and payment stoped at Po in Portland
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 32 above received letter from the Post Master Portland certifying the mail Route 365 No 14872 had not been paid.
The wind North West. Thermometer 37 degrees received letter from Hugh Mckay Lotterie Agent at Canada.
The wind South East. Thermometer 40 degrees above received duplicate check from the P.O. Department for the Quarter ending Sept 30. Wrote letter to G H Smith received letter from Hugh Mc Kay Canada.
The wind Eastt fresh breeze and big snow storm Thermometer 10 above zero. Went in the woods cutting firewood stormed so hard came out at noon received letter from Helen Stevens

The wind southerly and thick with snow. Started at 4oclock Am for Sullivan Steam boat to Carry Capt. N.A. Bickford and Dora Rand. At 10Am the wind northwest and clear. Thermometer 20 above. received letters from Emma M. Spurling
The wind North East and in the morning Thermometer at zero. In the afternoon snowy. received letter from Henry Geyer. Wrote letter to Mrs. Emma M. Spurling
The wind North East Thermometer 32 degrees Work one half day for James Gerrish hauling wood received letters from J. Wooster

The wind North West and in the morning Thermometer 25° Went to West Gouldsboro Oath to the P.M.So.Gouldsboro Hired Wm Bunker to Cary the Mail for a Quarter at $10 home at night received letter from Geo Hopkins Millbridge.

Calm in forenoon and overcast. In the afternoon wind North West fresh breeze. and pleasant. Thermometer 44 degrees Work one half day for Solomon Pendleton received letters from L A Emery & A P Wiswell

The wind Southerly and foggy all day Thermometer 50 degrees. took six Hhds salts out of the Black Warrior to use fishing Worked 1/2 day for Barney Foss on his boat to make her tight. received letter from Clarance Hale. Portland.
The wind Southerly and thick with fog. work apart of the day finishing dora sail that I had been making Thermometer 65 degrees received letter from S. Libby Town Treasurer.

Wind North West in forenoon South West in afternoon work all day haying hauled in 51 stacks of hay. Thermometer at noon was 78 degrees high received letter from C. J. Abbot. Atty at Law. Casting called for advertising in Boston Traveller.

The wind very moderate all day and fine weather went out fishing from home in dora. Thermometer in the afternoon when I came in from fishing 80 degrees. received letter from Helen Stevens at Leadsvelle
Wind South very fresh breeze and Rough by a long hard pull got to my troll. bait from the Weir. Thermometer 60 degrees at 5 PM. received letter from Geo.M.Warren Esq
Wind Southerly and thermometer 75 degrees did not go a fishing for the want of bait washed out fish for my self received letter from R H Bickford wrote one to Clarance Hane & Geo Warren.
Wind North in the morning Went out fishing with Barney Foss. got one tub of large hake to my part wind southerly in afternoon Thermometer 54 degrees received letter from W. F. Vase.
Wind South fresh breeze and cloudy Went out fishing. Thermometer at dark when I got home 49 degrees. received letter from Henry Handy
The wind Southerly and very moderate all day Thermometer 61 at noon. Went to So. Gouldsboro and worked all day for Charles L Bunker on shed back at night. received letter from Geo M. Warren

Calm nearly all day at night Wind North West Thermometer 32 degrees in the shade. Work in forenoon for J.D. Harrington on barn. in afternoon on freight house on Steam boat wharf repairing received letter from W. F. Vose.

Wind North East. Work about home in the forenoon but in the afternoon wind hauled Southerly. Went on board the Chromo and shoveled snow and commenced making boom for jib. received letter from Boardman Bros Calais dated 19th saying the ice was about as solid as anything during the winter did not think would break up till 15 or 20 of next month

Wind Southerly Went to town after a freight to go East with after the vessel is discharged bound non. received letter from Hugh McDonald one of owners of Chromo stating he was at Weehawken. Went to his boarding house at Weekawken and stopped with him all night

Wind Southerly commenced discharging cargo of stone. Went to town in the forenoon and took a coal order (without any help of a broker). to go Portsmouth N.H. with a load of coal freight $1.10 to be loaded at Port Johnston. In the afternoon went to Coney Island with my wife Took the Steamer on the North River and went to Bay Ridge then took the Cars to Coney Island Came back at night to the Chromo. The fare for Gentleman 40 cents and return. And for ladies 35 cts. Received letter today that Stella Our girl at home is sick but on the mending hand
Shooting match all day in the evening to Christmas tree at the Hall.
The wind Southly and foggy hunting the Oxen to haul lumber for Wm. Dodge commenced to make side table
The wind south west went to Shooting match
The wind Northerly hunted all day for freight took up at night to go to Boston wrote letter to James Staples Lubec for a freight
The wind Northerly hunted all day for freight took up at night to go to Boston wrote letter to James Staples Lubec for a freight
The wind Westerly went on Grind Stone point hunting foxes with hounds
Wind very moderate all day N.N.W. Tood tug boat and towed to Calais at 10 AM. Hunted around the remainder of the day for a freight but could not find any.

Wind North West in morning hunted untill noon for a man to go a trip to New Bedford & got one. then wind South West, at 1 P.M. got underway at Winter Harbor and went out. At dark wind Westerly. and at 10 PM passed Mt Desert Rock Light midnight wind West North West So ends these 24 hours

Wind East North East Went on Grindstone point with Nicholas Bunker hunting foxes with a hound got none. In the afternoon helped Mr Farrows of Rockland take the Mlasure of the Sch Chromo for a suit of sails at the wharf Winter Harbor.
The wind N.N.West. wrote letter to J. A Milliken Cherryfield. Work hauling stone around the house. received letters from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles. And C C Burril at Ellsworth.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 50° hauled stone all day grading in front of house.

Calm in the morning Got underway at day light and drifted down with the tide. as far as the lower End of Burrying Island the tide turned flood and anchored. at 10 An the wind breezed up S.S.W. got the anchor and undertook to beat dnon and run a shore one the musslebed. run Cage and and leave it home at dark run small anchor. and at midnight hove of went down abrest of Crabtrees stone and anchored

Wind Northerly and Westerly No berth to discharge stone. Went to fed Tuuge to leo 47 watin Street and got and order for Locon to load at Haboren for South New Mauket N.H. above Portsmouth freight $1.75 per ton with the accostumed towage

Calm in morning at 4 AM took tug boat and towed through the Gates wind breezed up S passed Eatons Neck at 4 PM Passed Hortons Point at 6.30 PM Passed Race Rock at 10 P.M. very cloudy and looking very much like a stone, but am in hope to make Point Judith at midnight saw Point Judith light and run for Vineyard Sound Light vessel

Wind North North East very fresh breeze in forenoon and showery all day. Went to Franklin to see Mr. J. P. Gordons Agent about loading stone but the wind blowing out from Mr Gordons wharf & cannot get this wharf therefore have decided to load for Portland

Wind North North East very fresh breeze in forenoon and showery all day. Went to Franklin to see Mr. J. P. Gordons Agent about loading stone but the wind blowing out from Mr Gordons wharf & cannot get this wharf therefore have decided to load for Portland

Wind North East and showery. Hauled into Crabtree & Harveys wharf in the morning and commenced loading paving blocks for Portland and at night had in 15 blocks The blocks are to fill a Chicago contract and are going through to Chicago by Rail from Portland The freight on stone $10 per 1.000

Wind NorthWest in the morning. Chromo was discharged at 9 oclock A.M. Settled for freight t noon got ship stones at at 2 oclock in the afternooon took tow boat and towed from Ipswich to Sea. Wind struck South East and gradually hauled back Westerly. At 8.30 passed Boon Island Leidge At midnight abrest of Cape Elizabeth when the wind Struck South

Wind NorthWest in the morning. Chromo was discharged at 9 oclock A.M. Settled for freight t noon got ship stones at at 2 oclock in the afternooon took tow boat and towed from Ipswich to Sea. Wind struck South East and gradually hauled back Westerly. At 8.30 passed Boon Island Leidge At midnight abrest of Cape Elizabeth when the wind Struck South

Wind Southerly commenced discharging cargo of stone. Went to town in the forenoon and took a coal order (without any help of a broker). to go Portsmouth N.H. with a load of coal freight $1.10 to be loaded at Port Johnston. In the afternoon went to Coney Island with my wife Took the Steamer on the North River and went to Bay Ridge then took the Cars to Coney Island Came back at night to the Chromo. The fare for Gentleman 40 cents and return. And for ladies 35 cts. Received letter today that Stella Our girl at home is sick but on the mending hand

Calm. I have decided I can take more stone and have taken 75 ft more edgestone. At 3 oclock P.M. took the tug boat and went over the Falls wind fresh South East made sail and went out the Bay. and anchored at Winter Harbor at midnight

Wind Southerly harnessed the horse in the morning and went back to Sullivan then hired a team again and went to Franklin to see about a load. but finding nothing that suited we came back to West Sullivan and agreceived to load random stone for New York for Crabtree & Havy for $1.25 oer net ton stone. to be weighed in Sullivan and I am to wait untill the Harvard Havy is loaded and she has not commenced yet
The wind Westerly finished repairing E. Grover's dora traded guns with T. R. Hammond.
